 The model for this SVM is similar to the typical SVM model except with
 some binary integer variables and constraints on those variables: the standard
 SVM (with data 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,k$
\end_inset

 and class assignments 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\in\left\{ -1,1\right\} $
\end_inset

) is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\min_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}} & \left\Vert \boldsymbol{\alpha}\right\Vert \\
\text{s.t.} & y_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}\cdot\mathbf{x}_{i}-\beta\right)\geq1\,\forall i\in\left\{ 1,\dots,k\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

incomplete SVM
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 introduces two new binary integer variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 They are incorporated as such: 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
determines whether constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}\cdot\mathbf{x}_{i}-\beta\right)\geq1\iff y_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}\cdot\mathbf{x}_{i}-\beta\right)-1\geq0$
\end_inset

 is active.
 This is effected by multipltying the constraint by 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}:$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b_{i}\left(y_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}\cdot\mathbf{x}_{i}-\beta\right)-1\right)\geq0
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 then the constraint is left as is and if 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 then the constraint is automatically satisfied as 
\begin_inset Formula $0\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then the constraint on how many constraint equations can be active is effected
 by using 0-norm:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert \mathbf{b}\right\Vert _{0}\geq100-K
\]

\end_inset

The sparsity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is controlled by 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 in the same way.
 The margin constraints transform further into 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b_{i}\left(y_{i}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}p_{i}\alpha_{i}x_{i}-\beta\right)-1\right)\geq0
\]

\end_inset

and maximum 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

density
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (as opposed to sparsity) is controlled by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert \mathbf{p}\right\Vert _{0}\leq M
\]

\end_inset

Therefore the model is for some 
\begin_inset Formula $K,M$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\min_{\underset{\underset{,\mathbf{p}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{n}}{\mathbf{b}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{k}}}{\boldsymbol{\alpha}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}}} & \left\Vert \boldsymbol{\alpha}\right\Vert \\
\text{s.t.} & b_{i}\left(y_{i}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}p_{i}\alpha_{i}x_{i}-\beta\right)-1\right)\geq0\,\forall i\in\left\{ 1,\dots,k\right\} \\
\left\Vert \mathbf{b}\right\Vert _{0} & \geq100-K\\
\left\Vert \mathbf{p}\right\Vert _{0} & \leq M
\end{align*}

\end_inset


