Claim: For 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ v_{1},\dots,v_{m}\right\} \subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq n+2$
\end_inset

 there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\alpha}=\left(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{m}\right)\neq\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{m}\alpha_{i}v_{i}=0
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{m}\alpha_{i}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq n+2$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{i}=\begin{pmatrix}v_{i}\\
1
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{\left(n+1\right)}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq n+2$
\end_inset

 it's the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $m>n+1$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ w_{1},\dots,w_{m}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is linearly dependent (since the maximal number of linearly independent
 vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{\left(n+1\right)}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

).
 Therefore, with 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\left(w_{1},w_{2},\dots,w_{m}\right)$
\end_inset

 it must be case that there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\alpha}\in\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
W\boldsymbol{\alpha} & =\begin{pmatrix}v_{1} & \cdots & v_{m}\\
1 & \cdots & 1
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}\alpha_{1}\\
\vdots\\
\alpha_{m}
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}\sum_{i=1}^{m}\alpha_{i}v_{i}\\
\sum_{i=1}^{m}\alpha_{i}
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =\mathbf{0}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
